			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: The Taken King &amp; Patch 2.0
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1841062">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Dramadon</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=7fc66ab734cac309c8890df4e482c46e&amp;p=1840849#post1840849" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">So are you saying this game is worth giving another shot?</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>This is the first cinematic you get in the expansion (spoilers obviously, although it's the first cinematic if you played the release game):<br />

<iframe class="restrain" title="YouTube video player" width="640" height="390" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/rAZOVt4K8Tw?wmode=opaque" frameborder="0"  allowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen  mozallowfullscreen ></iframe>
<br />
<br />
The voice you hear at the start is the new voice for your Ghost, by Nolan North, who replaced Peter Dinklage.  I think even Dinklages mediocre lines were better than Norths, but Dinklage had some terrible lines.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>store for what happened between release and The Taken King</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != 'inline') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'inline'; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none';  this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
<br />
<br />
All of this shit with the Hive has to be learned from Grimoire Cards, and almost no story:<br />
<br />
<b>In the Dark Below</b>, a guardian returns from being trapped by the Hive.  Her name is Eris, and she babbles nonsense most of the time about being blind.  She was part of a team of 6 that attempted to take down Crota, and failed.  She was trapped with the Hive, and hid for several years, losing her eyes and probably sanity.  No one thought the Hive were a big deal really, since they took the moon, and then completely ignored humanity after that.  Since they so thoroughly destroyed us, everyone happily turned a blind eye, and decided they weren't a threat anymore, since they were too powerful to worry about (humorously, the Vex are the most awe inspiring evil ever, but they're time travelers, so after you defeat them in the original game and raid, they're not really around in great numbers).<br />
<br />
It turns out that the Hive just want to fight the biggest strongest beings in the Galaxy to become worthy of their masters, who could be the Darkness or could be &lt;redacted name of mythological enemies&gt;.  So after they decimated the humans, humans weren't particularly worthy of their notice anymore.  <br />
<br />
The Hive Gods are nearly unstoppable.  Their physical body is a manifestation of their will from their true form inside the Netherworld.  The Hive are attempting to summon this invincible body to destroy Earth, but the Guardian stops it during the Dark Below story missions, and then takes out the summoners in the Strike Missions.  The Guardian then assembles 5 others (aka you go on the Raid) and goes into the Netherworld, and defeats Crota.<br />
<br />
<b>In the House of Wolves</b>, you get a lot of actual storyline.  Grimoire stuff is back story and detail, but you get a decent amount of storyline by playing the game.  When the Eliksni (also known as the Fallen) initially attacked humanity, one tribe, the House of Wolves got caught up in a war in the Asteroid Belt around Ceres by the Awoken.  The Awoken eventually won, and killed the Kell (king) of their tribe, and placed their nobles into the Prison of Elders.  One of the nobles, Skolas, gains his freedom and unites the clans, then goes around attempting to create a unified Fallen Force to destroy all humans and neo-humans (Awoken, Exo).  He almost destroys the Awoken Queen, Mara Sov, because she used Fallen as her bodyguards, and they turned on her.  Eventually the player captures Mara Sov, she puts him back into the Prison of Elders, and then the Guardian (player) can assemble a team to go into the prison and fight Skolas to the death (basically the Prison of Elders has a Thunderdome)<br />
 
</div>
</div>
</div><br />
<br />
The Taken King expansion is Oryx coming to finish the job the Hive failed in The Dark Below..  This expansion plays a lot like Wrath of the Lich King.  Except instead of Arthas, it's Oryx, and he isn't as cheesy. Honestly on several missions I would notice I was getting tense, even though the expansion is aimed at level 25 players, and I was starting at 38.<br />
<br />
With the House of Wolves DLC the game was fun enough that I was enjoying playing it casually.  I'm playing this as hard as any of the MMO's I've played during the first few weeks.  Not a huge desire to do the raids, but if they're as well done as the rest of the expansion, I'll probably try it out one day.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
		        		<blockquote class="signature restore"><div class="signaturecontainer">"Complaining is the modern metagame" - BNet forums</div></blockquote>
				
                                        
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
